<exercise>
<statement><p>
Let <m>\vp=\llt -1,4,2\rgt ,\ \vq=\llt 3,1,-1\rgt ,\ \vr=\llt 2,-3,-1\rgt </m>.
Check, by direct computation, that
<ol label="a">
<li> <m>\vp\times\vp=\vZero</m>
</li>
<li> <m>\vp\times\vq=-\vq\times\vp</m>
</li>
<li> <m>\vp\times(3\vr)=3(\vp\times\vr)</m>
</li>
<li> <m>\vp\times(\vq+\vr) = \vp\times\vq+\vp\times\vr</m>
</li>
<li> <m>\vp\times(\vq\times\vr) \ne (\vp\times\vq)\times\vr</m>
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
(a) See the solution.
</p>

<p>(b) <m>\vp\times\vq = -\vq\times\vp = \llt -6,5,-13\rgt</m>
</p>

<p>(c) <m>\vp \times (3\vr) = 3(\vp\times\vr) =  \llt 6,9,-15\rgt</m>
</p>

<p>(d) <m>\vp\times(\vq+\vr) = \vp\times\vq+\vp\times\vr =  \llt -4,8,-18\rgt</m>
</p>

<p>(e) <m>\vp\times(\vq\times\vr) = \llt -46,-19,15\rgt</m>,
    <m>(\vp\times\vq)\times\vr = \llt -44,-32,8\rgt</m>
</p>

</answer>

<solution><p>
<md>
<mrow>
\vp\times\vp
&amp;= \det\left[ \begin{matrix}\hi&amp;\hj&amp;\hk\cr-1&amp;4&amp;2\cr-1&amp;4&amp;2\end{matrix}\right] \tag{a}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\hi(4\times2-2\times4)-\hj(2-(-2))
+\hk(-4-(-4)) \notag
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= \llt 0,0,0\rgt \notag
</mrow>
<mrow>
\vp\times\vq
&amp;= \det\left[ \begin{matrix}\hi&amp;\hj&amp;\hk\cr-1&amp;4&amp;2\cr3&amp;1&amp;-1\end{matrix}\right]\tag{b}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\hi(-4-2)-\hj(1-6)
+\hk(-1-12)\notag
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= \llt -6,5,-13\rgt\notag
</mrow><mrow>
\vq\times\vp
&amp;= \det\left[ \begin{matrix}\hi&amp;\hj&amp;\hk\cr3&amp;1&amp;-1\cr-1&amp;4&amp;2\end{matrix}\right]\notag
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\hi(2+4)-\hj(6-1)
+\hk(12+1)\notag
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;
= \llt 6,-5,13\rgt \notag
</mrow>
<mrow>
\vp\!\times\!(3\vr)
&amp;= \det\left[ \begin{matrix}\hi&amp;\hj&amp;\hk\cr-1&amp;4&amp;2\cr6&amp;-9&amp;-3\end{matrix}\right]\tag{c}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\hi(-12+18)-\hj(3-12)
+\hk(9-24)
\notag
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;
= \llt 6,9,-15\rgt \notag
</mrow><mrow>
3(\vp\times\vr)
&amp;= 3\det\left[ \begin{matrix}\hi&amp;\hj&amp;\hk\cr-1&amp;4&amp;2\cr2&amp;-3&amp;-1\end{matrix}\right]\notag
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=3\Big(\hi(-4+6)-\hj(1-4)
+\hk(3-8) \Big)
\notag
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= \llt 6,9,-15\rgt \notag
</mrow>
</md>
(d) As <m>\vq+\vr=\llt 5,-2,-2\rgt </m>
<md>
<mrow>
\vp\times(\vq+\vr)
&amp;= \det\left[\begin{matrix}\hi&amp;\hj&amp;\hk\cr-1&amp;4&amp;2\cr5&amp;-2&amp;-2\end{matrix}\right]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\hi(-8+4)-\hj(2-10)
+\hk(2-20)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=  \llt -4,8,-18\rgt
</mrow>
</md>
(e) Using the values of <m>\vp\times\vq</m> and <m>3(\vp\times\vr)</m> computed
in parts (b) and (c)
<me>
\vp\times\vq+\vp\times\vr=\llt -6,5,-13\rgt +\frac{1}{3}\llt 6,9,-15\rgt
 = \llt -4,8,-18\rgt
</me>
<md>
<mrow>
\vq\times\vr
&amp;= \det\left[\begin{matrix}\hi&amp;\hj&amp;\hk\cr3&amp;1&amp;-1\cr2&amp;-3&amp;-1\end{matrix}\right]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\hi(-1-3)-\hj(-3+2)
+\hk(-9-2)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= \llt -4,1,-11\rgt
</mrow>
<mrow>
\vp\times(\vq\times\vr)
&amp;= \det\left[\begin{matrix}\hi&amp;\hj&amp;\hk\cr-1&amp;4&amp;2\cr-4&amp;1&amp;-11\end{matrix}\right]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\hi(-44-2)-\hj(11+8)
+\hk(-1+16)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= \llt -46,-19,15\rgt
</mrow>
<mrow>
(\vp\times\vq)\times\vr
&amp;= \det\left[\begin{matrix}\hi&amp;\hj&amp;\hk\cr-6&amp;5&amp;-13\cr2&amp;-3&amp;-1\end{matrix}\right]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\hi(-5-39)-\hj(6+26)
+\hk(18-10)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= \llt -44,-32,8\rgt
</mrow>
</md>
</p>
</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Calculate the area of the triangle with vertices <m>(0,0,0)</m>,
<m>(1,2,3)</m> and <m>(3,2,1)</m>.
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
<m>2\sqrt{6}</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Denote by <m>\theta</m> the angle between the two vectors
<m>\va=\llt 1,2,3\rgt</m> and <m>\vb=\llt 3,2,1\rgt</m>. The area of the triangle is one
half times the length, <m>|\va|</m>, of its base times its height
<m>h=|\vb|\sin\theta</m>.
</p>
<sidebyside width="28%">
  <image source="pfigs/sec_1_2_triangle"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
Thus the area of the triangle is  <m>\half|\va|\,|\vb|\,\sin\theta</m>.
By property 2 of the cross product in Theorem <xref ref="thm_crossPppties"/>,
 <m>|\va\times\vb|=|\va|\,|\vb|\,\sin\theta</m>. So
<md>
<mrow>
\text{area} &amp;= \half|\va\times\vb|
=\half|\llt 1,2,3\rgt\times\llt 3,2,1\rgt|
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\half | \hi\,(2-6)-\hj\,(1-9) +\hk\,(2-6)|
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\half\sqrt{16+64+16}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=2\sqrt{6}
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M200 2003D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
 A particle <m>P</m> of unit mass whose position in space at time
<m>t</m> is <m>\vr(t)</m> has angular momentum <m>L(t)=\vr(t)\times\vr'(t)</m>.
If <m>\vr''(t)=\rho(t)\vr(t)</m> for a scalar function <m>\rho</m>, show that
<m>L</m> is constant, i.e. does not change with time. Here <m>'</m> denotes
<m>\diff{}{t}</m>.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Evaluate <m>\diff{L}{t}</m> by differentiating <m>\vr(t)\times\vr'(t)</m>.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
See the solution.
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
The derivative of <m>L</m> is
<md>
<mrow>
\diff{L}{t}&amp;=\diff{}{t}\big(\vr(t)\times\vr'(t)\big)
=\vr'(t)\times\vr'(t)+\vr(t)\times\vr''(t)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\vr'(t)\times\vr'(t)+\vr(t)\times\big(\rho(t)\vr(t)\big)
</mrow>
</md>
Both terms vanish because the cross product of any two parallel vectors
is zero. So <m>\diff{L}{t}=0</m> and <m>L(t)</m> is independent of <m>t</m>.
</p></solution>
</exercise>
</exercisegroup>


